  <h1>Types of Civil Rights Violations Under § 1983</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Riley Chen (RC), Employment &amp; Civil Rights Practice Lead. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <p>Section 1983 is a vehicle, not a substantive right &mdash; it provides a remedy for violations of independently existing constitutional and federal statutory rights. The most litigated claim categories are described below.</p>
  <h2>Fourth Amendment: search, seizure, and force</h2>
  <p>The Fourth Amendment prohibits unreasonable searches, seizures, and uses of force. Actionable under &sect; 1983 when a government actor violates these protections. The objective reasonableness standard (from <em>Graham v. Connor</em> for force; <em>Illinois v. Gates</em> for searches) governs. Key variables: whether a warrant existed, whether a recognized exception applied, and whether the level of force was proportionate to the threat.</p>
  <h2>Fourteenth Amendment: due process</h2>
  <p>Two strands: Procedural due process (was adequate procedure provided before deprivation of life, liberty, or property?) and Substantive due process (was the government action arbitrary or conscience-shocking, regardless of procedure?). Wrongful conviction cases, inadequate medical care in prisons, and deprivation of parental rights are common due process claims.</p>
  <h2>Fourteenth Amendment: equal protection</h2>
  <p>Government actors may not discriminate based on race, national origin, sex (and in some contexts, sexual orientation and gender identity). Selective enforcement claims &mdash; where a person is targeted for enforcement based on their protected characteristic &mdash; fall here. These claims require showing discriminatory intent, not just disparate impact.</p>
  <h2>First Amendment retaliation</h2>
  <p>When a government actor takes adverse action in response to protected speech, assembly, or association. Police arresting protesters for their views, employers retaliating against public employee speech, or government officials threatening consequences for criticism all fall here. The key questions: was the speech protected? Was it a substantial factor in the adverse action?</p>
  <h2>Eighth Amendment: cruel and unusual punishment</h2>
  <p>Applies to convicted prisoners. Claims include excessive force by prison staff, failure to provide adequate medical care (deliberate indifference standard from <em>Estelle v. Gamble</em>), and prison conditions that deprive prisoners of basic human needs. Pretrial detainees are protected by the Fourteenth Amendment (lower deliberate indifference threshold after <em>Kingsley v. Hendrickson</em> for force claims).</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-section-1983-works">how section 1983 works</a> and <a href="/guides/what-to-do-after-civil-rights-violation">what to do after a civil rights violation</a>.</p>
